☀️🐔 How To Keep Your Chickens Cool In The Heat! Here are some tips 🫶🏻

👉🏻 Shade

👉🏻 Ventilated Coop

👉🏻 Ice Cold Treat 🧊 Add some ice, chia seeds (mimics bugs & makes the chickens want to peck the water!), parsley or oregano, frozen fruit (avoid corn!), and some water!

👉🏻 Dust Bath (you can create your own dust bathing area with an old tire, or plastic pool, add some soil, wood ash, and diatomaceous earth or First Saturday Lime)

👉🏻 Electrolytes (only 1 water source WITH & 1 water source WITHOUT) read the directions on the packets you buy. You can find them at any local feed store. Rooster Booster makes for a great supplement! 

•

For more tips check out our Chicken Heat Safety Tips blog with the link in our bio!

☀️ It ain’t new surprise that the heat is hurting our chickens in terms of laying eggs. We can try & cool them down the best we can, but it still affects their laying. I love to give my gals extra calcium during this time, their bodies are so stressed already, that needing that calcium boost will take some extra stress off their bodies.
I highly recommend @grubterra (& thank y’all for sending me this bag!) mealworms are totally great, BUT
👉🏻Black Soldier Fly Larvae have 75% MORE calcium than mealworms.
👉🏻Produces stronger egg shells (mine have been sooo brittle during this heat wave!)
👉🏻Healthy feathers
👉🏻Farm Raised (& environmental friendly!)
Feed as a “treat” not as a substitute for their regular feed.

#RawMilk - I’m sure folks come over & they see this in my fridge & immediately go “😳 gross”

But it’s def not! 😁 this is how I use/store my raw milk. I like that I’m able to “separate” the cream and the milk, since I DO buy in bulk 👉🏻 freeze 👉🏻 then defrost, the milk & cream just never go back together cohesive for me well enough (& my kids don’t like clumps of cream in their milk!). This drink dispenser works like a charm! When it starts to get low, I tip it some, to continue to only get milk & then will just pour that cream into a mason jar & use it for other things. (Butter, whip cream, coffee, cooking, etc)
👉🏻Once defrosted & the milk is in this dispenser, I use it within the week. (Milk doesn’t last long here!) it has never gotten “funky” on me.
•
Now when the milk is FRESH from the farm, I’ll leave it in the gallon it comes in because the milk & cream mix together beautifully & my kids enjoy it like that. The farm I use is 1.5hrs away, so I gotta freeze in bulk 😜

Fun Fact: Hens do not need a rooster in order to lay eggs. 🥚
👉🏻Hens will lay with or without a rooster. (& May actually prefer NO rooster around bothering them! 😜)
•
Might seem silly & “common knowledge” to some, but I get this question a lot 😊

👉🏻Having a rooster means your eggs will potentially be fertilized. I say potentially, because sometimes the Rooster doesn’t get the deed done with that particular hen 😜
👉🏻Fertile eggs are still safe to eat!

🥛 Freezing raw milk; I buy in bulk from a “local” farm (I say local but it’s 1.5hrs away lol). I typically buy 8 gallons priced at $8 each.
👉🏻I freeze the gallons in the same container they come in, then defrost when needed. Takes a few days in the fridge to defrost OR typically I “speed” defrost by submerging in water for a day. 😅
👉🏻The cream does not combine well once defrosted, so I usually scoop that out & use for other things. (Cream for coffee, cooking, butter, etc). 🐄
👉🏻We go through A LOT of milk. Usually 8 gallons will last me about 1-1.5 months. I have 3 kids who guzzle milk like their life depends on it 😂🫶🏻
👉🏻During my current pregnancy, whenever my stomach feels achey or nauseous, I drink a good ole glass of my raw milk & I feel better within minutes!
👉🏻If you comment with a negative comment about how “raw milk is bad for you”, etc. I implore you to do some research. Look up how many folks have gotten sick from salads, ice creams, etc from your large grocery stores FIRST compared to raw milkers. 😋 (also I implore you to read labels on any and all foods in the grocery store cause honestly, ain’t nothing we eating good for us anymore lol)

🍎 Apple Cider Vinegar 🍎
👉🏻Did you know that adding ACV to your chickens water is amazingly good for them? It’s the easiest way (in my opinion) to add some additional health benefits to your flock.
👉🏻Just make sure the ACV still has some of the “mother” in it!
👉🏻I buy (3) 32 oz jars at Costco for about $10 & they last me usually 2 months or so.
👉🏻I eyeball my measurements! I don’t have time to have a measuring spoon with me 🤪 but if you want an exact measurement it’s on the slides!

✨ Fun Fact ✨ Chickens can see color better than humans!

Yep! Chickens can see color/shades better than us. I mean, I think we all knew they were superior to humans, but this is just a cherry on top. 🍒

👉🏻Chickens are “tetrachromatic”; which means 4 types of cones to see light.
👉🏻In addition to red, green, and blue light; chickens can see ultraviolet light (think, black light).
👉🏻Chickens love the color RED. Blood, barn color, food, etc; watch out for red because they are drawn to it and go crazy for it! ❤️
